Culiseta indica
was identified during extensive mosquito faunal surveys in the Himalayan region of the former state of Jammu & Kashmir, India . Notable distinctive characteristics were observed in features of the male genitalia, including the bend at the middle of the setae on the basal mesal lobe of the gonocoxite and the phallosome being long, cylindrical, rounded apically and hooked subapically, and consisting of two sclerotized plates open dorsally and ventrally. In contrast, in males of
Cs . alaskaensis
from the former USSR the setae of the basal mesal lobe are bent somewhat beyond mid-length (
). Also, larvae from India differ in the development of setae 4- and 6-C: seta 4-C usually has 3 branches (2–5) and seta 6-C has 3 branches, very rarely 4 branches on one side, whereas in larvae of
Cs. alaskaensis
from the former USSR seta 4-C usually has 5 or 6 branches (3–7) and seta 6-C usually has 4 branches (2–6) (
). Phylogenetic analysis of the barcode region of the COI gene, along with the morphological observations in this study, confirm the distinction of
Cs. indica
from
Cs. alaskaensis .
